00:00:01.670 --> 00:00:03.110
BRAD TEMPLETON: Welcome
to Authors at Google.

00:00:03.110 --> 00:00:03.790
I'm Brad Templeton.

00:00:03.790 --> 00:00:06.440
We're here today with Mez Naam,
who has written a new

00:00:06.440 --> 00:00:09.200
book called Nexus, nothing
to do with Google.

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:13.070
Yet his talk is going to be
about Google and your brain.

00:00:13.070 --> 00:00:16.550
Mez used to be at Microsoft,
where he was a product manager

00:00:16.550 --> 00:00:18.180
for Microsoft Outlook.

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:19.870
How many people remember
Microsoft Outlook?

00:00:22.450 --> 00:00:25.890
And also instrumental on
Internet Explorer.

00:00:25.890 --> 00:00:28.830
But of late he's become a light
in the transhumanist

00:00:28.830 --> 00:00:32.290
field, writing books about
what happens when new

00:00:32.290 --> 00:00:35.060
technologies actually change
what it means to be human.

00:00:35.060 --> 00:00:37.670
He has three books coming
out this year.

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:39.830
One of them is a science-- two
of them, actually, are science

00:00:39.830 --> 00:00:42.960
fiction novels, Nexus being the
science fiction novel as

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:44.520
well as a nonfiction novel.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:46.940
He's here to tell us about it
and some of the ideas that

00:00:46.940 --> 00:00:48.500
he's been promoting
in this field.

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:51.510
He also is a guest lecturer at
Singularity University, where

00:00:51.510 --> 00:00:55.440
I'm also present, and has been
working on changing the world

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:56.320
for a long time now.

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:57.482
Mez.

00:00:57.482 --> 00:00:57.890
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:57.890 --> 00:00:59.140
RAMEZ NAAM: Awesome.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:02.530
All right, thank you, Brad.

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:05.770
Thanks Matt Cutts as well, for
you guys for setting this up.

00:01:05.770 --> 00:01:08.570
Yeah, so I have a book
out called Nexus.

00:01:08.570 --> 00:01:11.720
I hear that a company, a
technology company in the

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:13.760
Valley has a similar product
or a product

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:15.010
with the same name.

00:01:15.010 --> 00:01:16.860
I'm waiting for the co-marketing
dollars.

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:20.600
So just contact me if you're
watching this.

00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:23.610
This is a science fiction novel
set in the near future,

00:01:23.610 --> 00:01:25.725
2040, which sounds like
a ways in the future.

00:01:25.725 --> 00:01:29.630
But it's as far ahead of us
as 1985 was behind us.

00:01:29.630 --> 00:01:30.920
That's how close it is.

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:33.610
The premise is that there is a
drug that you can take that's

00:01:33.610 --> 00:01:34.910
packaged as a drug.

00:01:34.910 --> 00:01:37.150
But it's actually a set of
nanodevices that attach to

00:01:37.150 --> 00:01:39.800
your brain and transmit
wirelessly what

00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:40.950
your brain is doing.

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:43.280
And so if two or more people
have this, their brains sort

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:44.140
of sync up.

00:01:44.140 --> 00:01:46.840
And you get weak telepathy,
is what Corey Doctorow

00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:47.870
described it as.

00:01:47.870 --> 00:01:50.230
And my protagonists are working
on enhancing this.

00:01:50.230 --> 00:01:51.620
They live in San Francisco.

00:01:51.620 --> 00:01:54.910
And there are various battles
between a US government agency

00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:57.980
that wants it illegal and a
foreign power that may or may

00:01:57.980 --> 00:01:59.520
not be using it for
mind control.

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:00.130
So it's a thriller.

00:02:00.130 --> 00:02:01.450
it's really fun.

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:04.310
The science in it is as
real as I can make it.

00:02:04.310 --> 00:02:06.870
Most of the science in it I
researched for a book I wrote

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:10.620
in 2005 called More Than Human
about the actual science of

00:02:10.620 --> 00:02:14.210
augmenting our minds
and bodies.

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:18.470
Now of course, we've seen this
idea of getting data in and

00:02:18.470 --> 00:02:21.880
out of the brain in science
fiction for a long time.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:24.990
We've seen in the Borg in Star
Trek, for instance, where

00:02:24.990 --> 00:02:27.770
connectivity of the brain makes
a super-organism that's

00:02:27.770 --> 00:02:29.180
very homogeneous.

00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:31.550
We've seen it in The Nexus,
where the great American

00:02:31.550 --> 00:02:34.940
philosopher, Keanu Reeves, gets
to say I know Kung Fu.

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:36.320
BRAD TEMPLETON: That was
actually called The Matrix.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:37.240
They haven't renamed it.

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:39.490
RAMEZ NAAM: Oh, sorry.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:42.620
This film with this guy.

00:02:42.620 --> 00:02:45.510
But we've also seen some people
talking about it in

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:46.570
other contexts.

00:02:46.570 --> 00:02:49.820
For instance, a certain
technologist here in Silicon

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:51.980
Valley said you can imagine
your brain being

00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:52.720
augmented by Google.

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:55.650
You'd think about the question
and Google would whisper an

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:56.890
answer into your ear.

00:02:56.890 --> 00:02:58.500
Or maybe Google could
just implant the

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:01.300
answer in your brain.

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:05.350
Sergey has said we'd like to
think about Google being the

00:03:05.350 --> 00:03:07.850
third half of your brain.

00:03:07.850 --> 00:03:11.590
So I kind of like that idea
of having 1.5 brains.

00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:13.340
You could have a bumper sticker
on your car that says

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:17.790
"my other brain is a data
center." As we all know,

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:20.640
Sergey is well on his
way to being an

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:24.950
augmented transhuman already.

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:29.250
So this leads to the question
of, could you have Google in

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:29.690
your brain?

00:03:29.690 --> 00:03:31.000
Well I'm a program manager.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.590
So I think about, what the
requirements for this product

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:34.640
if we want to build it?

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:37.480
Well, you want to have
five things, I think.

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:40.700
Data input, you've got to get
data into your brain.

00:03:40.700 --> 00:03:43.660
Data output, you've got to get
data out of your brain and

00:03:43.660 --> 00:03:46.530
into the machine or the cloud
or other people's brains.

00:03:46.530 --> 00:03:48.660
We're going to have to do some
encoding and decoding work,

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:53.270
because the format for this data
is probably not the same

00:03:53.270 --> 00:03:55.510
between our machines and
our brains currently.

00:03:55.510 --> 00:03:57.590
So we're going to have some
converters in there, some

00:03:57.590 --> 00:03:59.200
protocol shifting.

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:02.750
You want multiple data types,
at minimum, text, audio, and

00:04:02.750 --> 00:04:04.970
video, and hopefully some other
data types as well.

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:08.630
And of course it has to be safe,
secure, and deployable,

00:04:08.630 --> 00:04:11.170
private as well, which might
actually turn out to be the

00:04:11.170 --> 00:04:14.630
largest challenges of
this technology.

00:04:14.630 --> 00:04:16.730
So of course that sounds
like science fiction.

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:20.670
But what I'm going to tell you
is that very, very, very early

00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:24.360
versions of this are possible
now, that we have low

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:28.310
bandwidth, low fidelity
transport of various data

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:31.540
types in and out of the human
brain right now, and that it

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:33.870
is getting better very,
very quickly.

00:04:33.870 --> 00:04:35.800
Now why is it getting better.

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:36.820
Who's investing in this?

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:38.910
Is this a Google X project?

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:40.200
Mostly it's not.

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:43.260
It's really being developed
for medical reasons.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:46.200
There's a large number of deaf
people in the world, 20

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.000
million in the US who are
hearing impaired.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.230
Two million of them can't be
helped by normal hearing aids.

00:04:52.230 --> 00:04:54.400
They have what's called
sensorineural deafness.

00:04:54.400 --> 00:04:57.990
That means the inner ear hair
cells are damaged or

00:04:57.990 --> 00:04:59.160
completely gone.

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:02.470
And so they cannot turn sound
waves, vibrations in the air,

00:05:02.470 --> 00:05:04.440
into nerve impulses.

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:08.360
There's 1.3 million blind
people in the US.

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:11.870
There's two million paralyzed
people in the US alone.

00:05:11.870 --> 00:05:15.500
1 and 1/2 million people with
Parkinson's disease, which is

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:18.330
essentially not exactly
untreatable, but

00:05:18.330 --> 00:05:20.330
uncurable right now.

00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:23.510
5 and 1/2 million people
with a traumatic brain

00:05:23.510 --> 00:05:24.790
injury of some sort.

00:05:24.790 --> 00:05:29.000
This is a scan of the brain of
Phineas Gage, a very famous

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.360
patient you had a
railroad spike

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:33.300
launched through his head.

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:36.250
He lived through the process but
came out a very different

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:39.160
guy with a different
personality, and modifications

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:40.690
to his attention and
memory and so on,

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:42.760
and not for the better.

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:45.800
So at least 10 million people
in the US who are candidates

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.530
for this technology, and really
probably close to a

00:05:48.530 --> 00:05:51.320
quarter billion people in the
world who suffer from these

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:52.480
problems as well.

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:54.090
So that's the motive.

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:55.440
So how does this work?

00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:58.500
Well, there's a long history
of this technology.

00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:03.980
It goes back to 1870 when two
German physicians had this

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:07.630
crazy idea of an experiment to
show that the nervous system

00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:08.690
was electrical.

00:06:08.690 --> 00:06:10.810
It was so crazy that the
university, the University of

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:14.140
Berlin, , wouldn't allow
them to perform it.

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:17.790
So instead they used Hitzig's
dining room table.

00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:19.930
They put a dog to sleep
with anesthesia.

00:06:19.930 --> 00:06:22.880
And then they electrically
stimulated parts of its brain

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:24.110
and found that they
could cause its

00:06:24.110 --> 00:06:26.590
paws to move on demand.

00:06:26.590 --> 00:06:28.990
So that was the first indication
that the nervous

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:31.060
system is electrical.

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:34.430
We really got the first proof
that it's not just muscle

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:39.670
motion but actual cognition is
electrochemical in the 1950s

00:06:39.670 --> 00:06:41.590
thanks to this man,
Wilder Penfield.

00:06:41.590 --> 00:06:45.290
He was a neurosurgeon who worked
on a number of things.

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:48.070
But among them was surgery
for epileptics.

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:50.930
Back in that day, and continuing
to today, one of

00:06:50.930 --> 00:06:53.540
the techniques used for epilepsy
was called oblation.

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.660
What that meant was you did
brain surgery, found the part

00:06:56.660 --> 00:07:00.280
| the brain that was sending
out these incorrect signals

00:07:00.280 --> 00:07:02.420
leading to epilepsy,
and you cut it out.

00:07:02.420 --> 00:07:04.160
Now Penfield wanted
to minimize the

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:05.780
damage to his patients.

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:07.610
So he would electrically
probe the brain

00:07:07.610 --> 00:07:09.020
while they were awake.

00:07:09.020 --> 00:07:11.270
When he'd find the part of the
brain that was responsible for

00:07:11.270 --> 00:07:13.100
the seizures, they would
have a seizure.

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:14.860
So then he would know
to cut out just that

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:16.290
spot and nothing else.

00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:19.050
But when he simulated other
parts of the brain, he'd find

00:07:19.050 --> 00:07:22.200
that people would suddenly have
a waking dream, a vivid

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:25.420
smell, a vivid insight,
some emotion.

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:29.230
So that was the first conclusive
demonstration that

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:33.910
thinking and feeling and your
senses are electrical as well.

00:07:33.910 --> 00:07:37.020
From there the story
gets very weird.

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:41.110
In the 1960s, two scientists,
Jose Delgado and Robert Heath,

00:07:41.110 --> 00:07:44.830
one of them, in fact, funded by
the CIA, did a variety of

00:07:44.830 --> 00:07:48.220
experiments on animals and then
on humans to show that

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:51.090
they could control behavior
through electrical

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:51.730
stimulation.

00:07:51.730 --> 00:07:54.130
With electrodes implanted in
the brain, they could put

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:55.930
animals to sleep or
wake them up.

00:07:55.930 --> 00:07:59.880
They could make an animal hungry
or satiated, aggressive

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:01.250
or fearful.

00:08:01.250 --> 00:08:04.600
With one experiment in a troop
of monkeys, they could change

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:07.385
which monkey was the alpha
male of the troop by

00:08:07.385 --> 00:08:09.280
stimulating the right
parts of the brain.

00:08:09.280 --> 00:08:13.100
Delgado, a Spanish scientist,
was quite a showman.

00:08:13.100 --> 00:08:15.105
So he repeatedly did
this experiment.

00:08:15.105 --> 00:08:18.330
This is him in a bull
ring in Cordoba.

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:19.640
Delgado is the guy
on the right.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:20.260
He's got a cape.

00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:22.930
And you could just barely see
he's got something with an

00:08:22.930 --> 00:08:24.100
antenna here.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:26.510
The bull has been worked up
by someone else before.

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:28.070
So the bull starts
to lean forward.

00:08:28.070 --> 00:08:29.020
It's getting aggressive.

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:31.070
You could see more clearly, A,
there's something on the

00:08:31.070 --> 00:08:35.590
bull's head, and B, this black
box with a long antenna.

00:08:35.590 --> 00:08:37.510
The bull starts to charge him.

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:42.289
Delgado drops the cape and hits
the button on this radio

00:08:42.289 --> 00:08:43.659
device that he has.

00:08:43.659 --> 00:08:47.220
And the bull skids to a halt
because it's now terrified of

00:08:47.220 --> 00:08:51.750
him, because he has remotely
stimulated an input of

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:55.600
electricity to its fear
centers in its brain.

00:08:55.600 --> 00:08:57.540
I'm going to show you
a video of this.

00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:01.010
This video is from the French
documentary in the 1960s.

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:02.500
So it's in French.

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:04.800
It's not exactly HD.

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:07.220
Delgado is the guy in
white who appears a

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:08.140
little bit into it.

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:11.975
And watch how the bull reacts
to him at various times.

00:09:11.975 --> 00:09:18.180
