00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:57.780
Hi.

00:11:57.780 --> 00:12:01.260
-You've got that, Deb, right?

00:12:01.260 --> 00:12:02.510
-Hi Jonathan.

00:12:07.165 --> 00:12:09.840
Hi.

00:12:09.840 --> 00:12:12.200
-We call that a late
Christmas present.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:15.140
RAMEZ NAAM: So this is a life
changing technology.

00:12:15.140 --> 00:12:18.720
Like I said, 200,000 people
around the world have it now.

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:18.960
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:21.200
RAMEZ NAAM: This little boy
turned five in December and

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:22.700
he's still doing great.

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:24.860
Now I told you along the
requirements, we need to have

00:12:24.860 --> 00:12:26.870
data input into the brain.

00:12:26.870 --> 00:12:30.710
So I've just shown you proof of
principal of data input of

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:32.540
one data type, audio.

00:12:32.540 --> 00:12:33.670
Now we all care about
our hearing.

00:12:33.670 --> 00:12:34.980
It's very important to us.

00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:37.810
Another sense we care about
a fair bit is sight.

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:40.770
So let's see data
input for sight.

00:12:40.770 --> 00:12:44.300
This man, Jens Naumann, this
picture was on the cover of

00:12:44.300 --> 00:12:46.660
Wired magazine in 2002.

00:12:46.660 --> 00:12:50.750
Jens, when he was 18 years
old, worked on a railway.

00:12:50.750 --> 00:12:53.400
And one day with his
pick he struck

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:54.700
something he got was rock.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:55.760
It was steel.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:58.370
A little fragment came up and
destroyed one of his eyes.

00:12:58.370 --> 00:13:01.510
Lives in Canada, very active
fellow, refused to compromise

00:13:01.510 --> 00:13:02.680
about his lifestyle.

00:13:02.680 --> 00:13:05.350
The next year he was
out snowmobiling.

00:13:05.350 --> 00:13:09.320
And part of the clutch had a
problem and threw a fragment

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:11.970
of metal that destroyed
his other eye.

00:13:11.970 --> 00:13:14.030
And he was rendered blind
in both eyes.

00:13:14.030 --> 00:13:18.820
He was blind for 20 years, until
2002 when this happened.

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:22.630
So what he's wearing is a CCD
camera, not that different

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:24.020
from any digital camera today.

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:26.950
The cable here goes to a small
computer that he wore on his

00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:29.440
hip, actually it was about
this big back then.

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:32.050
And now it's probably the
size of a quarter.

00:13:32.050 --> 00:13:35.260
And from there the signal is
translated from the format of

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:37.660
the camera to one that his
brain can understand.

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:42.780
And it travels back up into a
jack in the back of his head,

00:13:42.780 --> 00:13:45.860
Matrix style.

00:13:45.860 --> 00:13:52.860
Jens has this system which has
256 electrodes, as opposed to

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:58.160
the many billions of neurons in
his primary visual cortex.

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:02.210
So again, there's a huge
mismatch in the size of the

00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:04.430
pipe to the size of the
system, if you will.

00:14:04.430 --> 00:14:06.400
You wouldn't think it
could possibly work.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:08.770
But if produces what they call
limited mobility vision.

00:14:08.770 --> 00:14:11.480
What does limited mobility
vision mean?

00:14:11.480 --> 00:14:12.950
Well, here's Jens.

00:14:12.950 --> 00:14:13.330
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:18.510
-I was able to very carefully
drive and look from my left

00:14:18.510 --> 00:14:22.190
side of my right side, making
sure I was between the row of

00:14:22.190 --> 00:14:25.010
trees on the right and the
building on the left.

00:14:25.010 --> 00:14:28.660
And when I got near any
obstruction in the front, I

00:14:28.660 --> 00:14:30.010
would see that there
was an obstruction.

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:32.280
I would also see the lack
of obstructions.

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:35.680
And went I backed up, I would
be able to inspect for

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:37.290
instructions there.

00:14:37.290 --> 00:14:39.855
It was really a nice feeling.

00:14:39.855 --> 00:14:40.110
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:14:40.110 --> 00:14:42.180
RAMEZ NAAM: It was really
a nice feeling.

00:14:42.180 --> 00:14:45.070
So that's a guy who was blind
for 20 years driving a Mustang

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:46.400
convertible.

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:48.280
Now Jens has terrible vision.

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:50.140
It's really, really atrocious.

00:14:50.140 --> 00:14:52.350
I wasn't in that parking lot
with him and you probably

00:14:52.350 --> 00:14:53.790
wouldn't want to be.

00:14:53.790 --> 00:14:57.580
But it's a big step up from
zero vision whatsoever.

00:14:57.580 --> 00:14:59.190
So that's data input.

00:14:59.190 --> 00:14:59.780
And throughout--

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:02.340
in the novel, you see examples
of people getting video and

00:15:02.340 --> 00:15:04.330
audio going straight
to their brain.

00:15:04.330 --> 00:15:05.520
But what about data output?

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:08.470
Can we get output out of
the brain to control

00:15:08.470 --> 00:15:10.570
systems or send data?

00:15:10.570 --> 00:15:12.730
Well we can and we have.

00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:15.870
So this is a doctor named Phil
Kennedy and a patient name

00:15:15.870 --> 00:15:16.840
Johnny Ray.

00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:20.540
Johnny Ray was 52 years old,
a Vietnam vet, drywall

00:15:20.540 --> 00:15:22.710
contractor, played
blues guitar.

00:15:22.710 --> 00:15:24.780
One day he had a
massive stroke.

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:28.370
He woke up in the VA hospital
in Atlanta, paralyzed

00:15:28.370 --> 00:15:30.070
from his neck down.

00:15:30.070 --> 00:15:32.060
And to save his life they
had to do an emergency

00:15:32.060 --> 00:15:32.910
tracheotomy.

00:15:32.910 --> 00:15:34.410
So he couldn't speak either.

00:15:34.410 --> 00:15:38.070
His only way to communicate was
to blink his eyes once for

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:39.480
a no and twice for yes.

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:40.740
That was it.

00:15:40.740 --> 00:15:43.930
This guy Kennedy had been
working in monkeys and had

00:15:43.930 --> 00:15:47.060
demonstrated that he could put
a single electrode in a

00:15:47.060 --> 00:15:49.350
monkey's motor cortex, the
part of their brain

00:15:49.350 --> 00:15:52.690
responsible for motion, and
train them to move a cursor

00:15:52.690 --> 00:15:54.830
around on a screen.

00:15:54.830 --> 00:15:57.500
He applied to the FDA for
permission to do it in a human

00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:58.870
patient for the first time.

00:15:58.870 --> 00:16:00.500
They said yes, with
some conditions.

00:16:00.500 --> 00:16:03.310
One of their conditions was
that he had to seal

00:16:03.310 --> 00:16:04.320
the skull back up.

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:06.730
They didn't want wires running
in and out of the skull and

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:09.180
having a risk of an infection
getting into the brain.

00:16:09.180 --> 00:16:10.470
So they made the system
wireless.

00:16:10.470 --> 00:16:12.740
It actually sits inside
of his brain.

00:16:12.740 --> 00:16:17.470
It gets power and data from a
cap that he wears, or from the

00:16:17.470 --> 00:16:19.710
equipment near his
hospital bed.

00:16:19.710 --> 00:16:23.070
Now this is the most extreme
case of this mismatch.

00:16:23.070 --> 00:16:25.320
Because it's literally one
electrode in Jonny Ray's

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:30.020
brain, but more than a million
neurons in his motor cortex.

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:33.930
But that gave him enough control
to be able to type out

00:16:33.930 --> 00:16:36.820
messages on an on-screen
keyboard, which is a dramatic

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:39.520
step up from just being able
to blink at people.

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:42.860
And this technology has gotten
better and better, and is in

00:16:42.860 --> 00:16:45.760
more serious human trials now.

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:49.220
And in fact, a video came out
just a couple months ago of a

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:51.910
woman using this to do something
tat was very, very,

00:16:51.910 --> 00:16:53.940
very important to her,
which was to

00:16:53.940 --> 00:16:57.200
have her morning coffee.

00:16:57.200 --> 00:16:58.120
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:16:58.120 --> 00:17:00.490
-You're watching the most
advanced brain machine

00:17:00.490 --> 00:17:02.360
interface in action.

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:05.540
Kathy Hutchinson is paralyzed
and unable to speak.

00:17:05.540 --> 00:17:08.369
But just by thinking, she's able
to control the movements

00:17:08.369 --> 00:17:12.140
of this robotic arm, and drink
her morning coffee.

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:14.720
She's part of a pioneering study
run by researchers at

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:17.030
Brown University in the US.

00:17:17.030 --> 00:17:20.930
-People who are paralyzed have
their brain disconnected from

00:17:20.930 --> 00:17:21.510
their body.

00:17:21.510 --> 00:17:22.720
So they're not able to--

00:17:22.720 --> 00:17:23.619
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:17:23.619 --> 00:17:27.310
RAMEZ NAAM: So we've seen data
input now of video and audio.

00:17:27.310 --> 00:17:29.650
We've seen data output
of motion.

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:32.120
And now in primates they have
data input as well.

00:17:32.120 --> 00:17:35.760
They have systems like this that
also sent touch data back

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:37.610
into the brain.

00:17:37.610 --> 00:17:40.280
There's one other domain that I
want to talk about, which is

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:42.120
Parkinson's, that I mentioned
early on.

00:17:42.120 --> 00:17:44.900
All Parkinson's drugs
fail over time.

00:17:44.900 --> 00:17:46.550
They just stop working
eventually.

00:17:46.550 --> 00:17:49.160
But now we're finding that with
something called a deep

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:52.140
brain stimulator, a single
electrode run very deep into

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:54.970
the brain, you can keep a
Parkinson's patient healthy

00:17:54.970 --> 00:17:57.110
and functional for
quite a while.

00:17:57.110 --> 00:17:58.460
And there's 80,000 of
these that have been

00:17:58.460 --> 00:18:00.640
implanted so far.

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:02.560
But interestingly enough,
they found some side

00:18:02.560 --> 00:18:03.570
effects with these.

00:18:03.570 --> 00:18:06.540
In some patients who got a deep
brain simulator who had

00:18:06.540 --> 00:18:08.650
previously untreatable
depression, that wouldn't

00:18:08.650 --> 00:18:11.900
respond to any drugs, they
suddenly had normal mood.

00:18:11.900 --> 00:18:16.970
In some patients that had
previously untreatable OCD,

00:18:16.970 --> 00:18:19.740
they found that suddenly they
had normal behavioral control.

00:18:19.740 --> 00:18:22.150
And so now there are clinical
trials going on of using this

00:18:22.150 --> 00:18:26.290
deep brain simulation for
depression and for OCD, both

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:28.880
of which seem to come
from very deep, old

00:18:28.880 --> 00:18:30.330
portions of our brain.

00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:34.090
Which, if you think about it,
is sort of the same sort of

00:18:34.090 --> 00:18:38.300
work that Jose Delgado was doing
in his animal control,

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:43.800
but in a much more benign,
therapeutic sort of context.

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:46.740
So that's what's happening
so far in humans.

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:48.130
But what are the
opportunities?

00:18:48.130 --> 00:18:50.260
And I did talk about this being
the science behind a

00:18:50.260 --> 00:18:51.210
science fiction novel.

00:18:51.210 --> 00:18:54.360
So it's not going to stop at
just this sort of thing.

00:18:54.360 --> 00:18:57.440
The opportunities are really
in the higher functions, if

00:18:57.440 --> 00:19:00.130
you will, memory, attention,
learning, the things that make

00:19:00.130 --> 00:19:03.290
us really human.

00:19:03.290 --> 00:19:06.070
In the film Memento,
Guy Pierce played

00:19:06.070 --> 00:19:07.220
the character Lenny.

00:19:07.220 --> 00:19:11.100
And Lenny can't form any
new long-term memories.

00:19:11.100 --> 00:19:12.090
He will see something.

00:19:12.090 --> 00:19:12.640
He'll learn it.

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:13.640
He understands it.

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:16.110
But within a few minutes, it's
gone from his memory.

00:19:16.110 --> 00:19:19.360
This is an extreme case, but
cases like this and many, many

00:19:19.360 --> 00:19:22.440
milder cases of this sort
exist in people who have

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:25.530
damage to part of their brain
called the hippocampus.

00:19:25.530 --> 00:19:28.000
If your hippocampus is damaged,
you can't form these

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.030
new memories.

00:19:29.030 --> 00:19:32.640
So working on this, scientists
have been trying to create an

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:36.560
artificial hippocampus, a
hippocampus chip that is

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:39.020
structured like the tissue in
the hippocampus, and that you

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:40.380
can shunt in.

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:43.780
So in a rat experiments, they
actually take a rat that has a

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:46.180
damaged hippocampus, this
area, and they put in

00:19:46.180 --> 00:19:50.460
bypasses, arrays of electrodes
basically, that put in place

00:19:50.460 --> 00:19:53.230
the hippocampus chip as a
replacement for the damaged

00:19:53.230 --> 00:19:54.690
brain tissue.

00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:58.660
And they found that they can
restore these rats' ability to

00:19:58.660 --> 00:20:01.160
learn new things, restore
their memory, which is

00:20:01.160 --> 00:20:03.770
awesome, has great application
for humans.

00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:05.120
But they went farther
than that.

00:20:05.120 --> 00:20:08.820
And they've show that they can
improve these rats' memories.

00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:10.960
They can improve the speed
at which they learn.

00:20:10.960 --> 00:20:14.110
They can keep the memories
around indefinitely because

00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:16.910
there's no need for the memory
in a chip to decay.

00:20:16.910 --> 00:20:19.180
And they can reactivate
that memory at will.

00:20:19.180 --> 00:20:22.020
They can put the rat back in a
maze that it's learned and

00:20:22.020 --> 00:20:25.330
reactivate the memory of that
maze's layout and have it have

00:20:25.330 --> 00:20:27.940
perfect recall what was going
on inside of that and how to

00:20:27.940 --> 00:20:32.860
find the water table or the
water platform at the end.

00:20:32.860 --> 00:20:37.210
So that's the early glimmers
of work that would actually

00:20:37.210 --> 00:20:39.980
potentially repair, and
maybe even improve,

00:20:39.980 --> 00:20:41.760
human higher functions.

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:45.200
We've also gone into what
we would think of as

00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:46.240
intelligence.

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:49.820
So in rhesus monkeys, people
have been working on a chip

00:20:49.820 --> 00:20:54.020
that goes into the frontal
cortex, the most executive

00:20:54.020 --> 00:20:57.960
part of your brain that
controls attention and

00:20:57.960 --> 00:21:01.000
thoughts and juggling various
different things are going on.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.200
So they take these
rhesus monkeys.

00:21:03.200 --> 00:21:05.450
They put this implant in
their frontal cortex.

00:21:05.450 --> 00:21:08.403
And they give them a monkey
IQ test, if you will.

00:21:08.403 --> 00:21:10.330
It's called a pick and match
test where they have to learn

00:21:10.330 --> 00:21:13.550
to match up certain
things together.

00:21:13.550 --> 00:21:16.890
And while this is happening, the
implant learns the pattern

00:21:16.890 --> 00:21:20.160
of what goes on in the neurons
of their frontal cortex when

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:22.900
they get it right and when
they get it wrong.

00:21:22.900 --> 00:21:26.160
So then they take these monkeys
and they impair them

00:21:26.160 --> 00:21:28.400
to get them to have a lower
score on the test.

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:31.400
They impair them by giving them
large doses of cocaine.

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:32.970
So the monkeys aren't
complaining.

00:21:32.970 --> 00:21:35.440
They're pretty happy with the
experiment, I think, but their

00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:37.550
scores actually do go down.

00:21:37.550 --> 00:21:41.090
Then in half the monkeys, they
put the implant into an active

00:21:41.090 --> 00:21:45.000
mode to see if it can
restore their skill.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:46.210
And it can.

00:21:46.210 --> 00:21:48.440
But it also goes farther
than that.

00:21:48.440 --> 00:21:52.910
The average score of the group
that was not impaired or

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:55.230
enhanced was 75.

00:21:55.230 --> 00:21:58.790
The group that had the implant
put into in active mode scored

00:21:58.790 --> 00:22:00.550
on average an 85.

00:22:00.550 --> 00:22:03.430
So they're actually using this
implant to improve the

00:22:03.430 --> 00:22:08.520
monkey's skill on this monkey IQ
test, if you will, which of

00:22:08.520 --> 00:22:11.740
course will lead to the cyborg
planet of the apes.

00:22:14.500 --> 00:22:17.240
But the real frontier, I
think, isn't so much in

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:20.240
enhancing individual
capabilities, though that is

00:22:20.240 --> 00:22:21.780
something that we will
actually look at.

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:24.300
It's really in communication.

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:28.210
Once upon a time, computers
were about solo work.

00:22:28.210 --> 00:22:30.960
You had a computer because it
was a fancy word processor,

00:22:30.960 --> 00:22:32.770
which really meant it was
a fancy typewriter.

00:22:32.770 --> 00:22:36.230
It was a fancy spreadsheet
machine, which really meant

00:22:36.230 --> 00:22:38.880
that it was a very fancy abacus,
in a certain sense.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:40.210
But that's not what
actually changed

00:22:40.210 --> 00:22:41.310
the world with computers.

00:22:41.310 --> 00:22:43.880
What's changed the world has
been their ability to

00:22:43.880 --> 00:22:48.620
communicate things between us,
and with the cloud overall.

00:22:48.620 --> 00:22:52.200
And that's the direction that I
think is most exciting about

00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:54.500
this sort of technology and the
direction that we really

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:57.320
go into in the novel.

00:22:57.320 --> 00:23:00.510
There is some work happening
on that today.

00:23:00.510 --> 00:23:03.420
DARPA is very interested in
all sorts of things that

00:23:03.420 --> 00:23:05.340
improve human performance.

00:23:05.340 --> 00:23:08.180
And they have a particular
program called the Enhanced

00:23:08.180 --> 00:23:10.310
Battlefield Communication
Program.

00:23:10.310 --> 00:23:13.820
And that program gave a grant
that funded this study.

00:23:13.820 --> 00:23:17.060
This study had two monkeys
in different rooms, with

00:23:17.060 --> 00:23:20.700
soundproofing between them,
wired together via implants in

00:23:20.700 --> 00:23:22.650
their auditory cortices, so the

00:23:22.650 --> 00:23:24.730
auditory part of the brain.

00:23:24.730 --> 00:23:28.740
They would play a sound
for monkey one.

00:23:28.740 --> 00:23:32.230
And what they found as they
hoped was that monkey two

00:23:32.230 --> 00:23:35.490
could hear that sound and could
identify it, could say

00:23:35.490 --> 00:23:36.620
what it was.

00:23:36.620 --> 00:23:40.140
And DARPA's dream is to build
implants for soldiers where

00:23:40.140 --> 00:23:42.720
the soldiers all have intuitive
knowledge of what's

00:23:42.720 --> 00:23:45.010
happening to the other soldiers
in their squad and

00:23:45.010 --> 00:23:47.320
the battlefield more broadly.

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:51.090
Real science happening,
not yet in humans.

00:23:51.090 --> 00:23:53.540
We've also recently--

00:23:53.540 --> 00:23:55.380
so now we've got motion
out of the brain.

00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:57.780
We've got audio out
of the brain.

00:23:57.780 --> 00:23:59.850
This is video out
of the brain.

00:23:59.850 --> 00:24:01.150
In humans--

00:24:01.150 --> 00:24:03.040
this study was done last year.

00:24:03.040 --> 00:24:07.940
They put subjects in an fMRI
machine, a brain scanner.

00:24:07.940 --> 00:24:11.070
It showed them a clip
from video.

00:24:11.070 --> 00:24:14.550
And then an algorithm tried to
match that clip to what they

00:24:14.550 --> 00:24:15.670
were actually seeing.

00:24:15.670 --> 00:24:19.010
So tried to match their brain
activity to what they were

00:24:19.010 --> 00:24:19.750
actually seeing.

00:24:19.750 --> 00:24:21.220
Because it's techies here,
I can talk about it

00:24:21.220 --> 00:24:22.210
a little bit more.

00:24:22.210 --> 00:24:26.020
What they actually did was the
algorithm had a library of

00:24:26.020 --> 00:24:29.500
fuzzed out video frames that it
could access, and a machine

00:24:29.500 --> 00:24:32.690
learning model that learned
how to-- or was trained to

00:24:32.690 --> 00:24:36.170
match up different patterns of
brain activity with the most

00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:40.700
likely clip from its
video library.

00:24:40.700 --> 00:24:44.120
And let's see how
it actually did.

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:47.155
Now this is very, very
early technology.

00:24:47.155 --> 00:24:49.860
But you can see that just seeing
what's happening in the

00:24:49.860 --> 00:24:53.920
patient's brain from the
outside, it gets some vague

00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:57.020
idea of what it is that
they're looking at.

00:25:10.590 --> 00:25:12.490
Which is exactly what
we'd expect.

00:25:12.490 --> 00:25:16.040
In general in the brain, the
same neurons fire, the same

00:25:16.040 --> 00:25:19.480
activity happens, when you're
seeing something, when you're

00:25:19.480 --> 00:25:22.130
imagining that thing, and when
you're remembering that thing.

00:25:22.130 --> 00:25:23.800
There's some difference in
higher order bits of the

00:25:23.800 --> 00:25:26.870
brain, but in the primary visual
areas or the primary

00:25:26.870 --> 00:25:29.210
auditory areas, it's the
same sort of thing.

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:31.380
All of this, by the way,
happened with brain scanners

00:25:31.380 --> 00:25:32.350
on the outside.

00:25:32.350 --> 00:25:35.050
And those are very, very
limited in how high the

00:25:35.050 --> 00:25:36.640
resolution they can get
is of what's going

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:37.640
on inside the brain.

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:40.240
With actual electrodes in the
brain, this quality would

00:25:40.240 --> 00:25:43.420
probably much, much higher.

00:25:43.420 --> 00:25:48.380
And now the team funded by DARPA
that did the hippocampus

00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:52.230
improvement for the rats is
looking at linking the

00:25:52.230 --> 00:25:55.760
hippocampi of two rats together
and seeing what could

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:58.510
happen, seeing if one rat who's
been trained to run the

00:25:58.510 --> 00:26:01.660
maze can convey that information
directly to

00:26:01.660 --> 00:26:04.050
another rat that's never
seen the same maze.

00:26:04.050 --> 00:26:06.830
Now like all experiments, the
first ones of this will almost

00:26:06.830 --> 00:26:09.460
certainly fail, but we will
eventually get there.

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:12.390
That's the kind of thing that
people are working on now.

00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:14.130
Then that leads, of course,
to Keanu Reeves

00:26:14.130 --> 00:26:16.900
saying, I know kung fu.

00:26:16.900 --> 00:26:18.040
Now let's talk practicality.

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:21.080
I've been spinning out what this
sci-fi world could look

00:26:21.080 --> 00:26:23.460
like and it's really fun to play
with, but there are some

00:26:23.460 --> 00:26:25.030
real limitations.

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:27.050
The first limitation
is quality.

00:26:27.050 --> 00:26:30.550
Can any of you say what this
image is on the right?

00:26:30.550 --> 00:26:33.110
If you've seen this example
before, please don't say.

