RAMEZ NAAM: On Jesus.

00:26:46.620 --> 00:26:50.060
So Jens Naumann, the blind guy,
he has 256 electrodes.

00:26:50.060 --> 00:26:53.330
He has a 16 by 16 pixel
display essentially.

00:26:53.330 --> 00:26:55.220
This is the quality
of his vision.

00:26:55.220 --> 00:26:57.140
So you can see why nobody wanted
to be in that parking

00:26:57.140 --> 00:26:58.500
lot when he was driving
in the car.

00:26:58.500 --> 00:27:00.320
He can basically see large
obstructions and not

00:27:00.320 --> 00:27:01.080
much more than that.

00:27:01.080 --> 00:27:03.250
So quality is a big
limitation.

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:06.360
And indeed, if you look at the
most sophisticated brain

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:09.090
computer interface we've ever
implanted in someone, has this

00:27:09.090 --> 00:27:12.350
256 electrode situation
right now.

00:27:12.350 --> 00:27:14.240
And that's largely because the
people who have been doing

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:17.570
this have been neurologists and
neuroscientists and not

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:18.790
electrical engineers.

00:27:18.790 --> 00:27:21.320
That's not who've been
doing it so far.

00:27:21.320 --> 00:27:22.780
But they are starting
to get into it.

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:25.620
And now you see labs devoted
entirely to developing the

00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:28.560
hardware that's being used
in these experiments.

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:31.970
University of Michigan has 1,000
electrode wireless chip.

00:27:31.970 --> 00:27:34.790
And a German company called
Infineon has a 16,000

00:27:34.790 --> 00:27:37.170
electrode wireless chip
that's coming on the

00:27:37.170 --> 00:27:38.180
market right now.

00:27:38.180 --> 00:27:41.360
So we will see that
bandwidth go up.

00:27:41.360 --> 00:27:44.180
And there's huge room
to improve.

00:27:44.180 --> 00:27:47.530
The chip in my laptop has about
a billion transistors in

00:27:47.530 --> 00:27:50.090
it in a size not much different
than some of these

00:27:50.090 --> 00:27:51.010
interfaces.

00:27:51.010 --> 00:27:53.470
Of course, these things are very
hot, but we don't have to

00:27:53.470 --> 00:27:54.630
run them at gigahertz.

00:27:54.630 --> 00:27:58.010
If you run them at 100 Hertz,
your going to pretty much

00:27:58.010 --> 00:27:59.550
match what the brain can do.

00:27:59.550 --> 00:28:02.860
So it's quite possible with
advanced technologies that we

00:28:02.860 --> 00:28:06.590
already have in other domains
to dramatically increase the

00:28:06.590 --> 00:28:08.580
bandwidth coming in and
out of the human

00:28:08.580 --> 00:28:10.320
brain in these systems.

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:14.080
And we don't have to go far for
it to suddenly look pretty

00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:16.670
functional in terms of restoring
functionality for

00:28:16.670 --> 00:28:17.850
someone who's been impaired.

00:28:17.850 --> 00:28:21.770
At 5,000 pixels, this is what
you see, which is a dramatic,

00:28:21.770 --> 00:28:24.320
dramatic step up from 256.

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:29.610
And 5,000 pixels is still
dramatically smaller than the

00:28:29.610 --> 00:28:35.760
type of technology that we use
in electronics traditionally.

00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:38.190
The other very big limitation
is this is your brain we're

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:39.780
talking about.

00:28:39.780 --> 00:28:42.870
Very few of us are going to
voluntarily have brain

00:28:42.870 --> 00:28:47.710
surgery, certainly not to get
256 pixel vision, or even the

00:28:47.710 --> 00:28:49.850
5,000 pixel vision.

00:28:49.850 --> 00:28:51.190
So this is a very big hurdle.

00:28:51.190 --> 00:28:53.040
In the book, I get around
this by saying, hey,

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:54.510
you swallow the drug.

00:28:54.510 --> 00:28:56.820
The nanoparticles go through
your blood-brain barrier and

00:28:56.820 --> 00:28:58.120
self assemble around
your neurons.

00:28:58.120 --> 00:28:59.990
It's all great.

00:28:59.990 --> 00:29:03.410
But that's not the technology
that we have today.

00:29:03.410 --> 00:29:07.020
Of course there have been other
cases where we've gone

00:29:07.020 --> 00:29:10.810
from something being so unsafe
and so impractical to being

00:29:10.810 --> 00:29:12.030
very practical.

00:29:12.030 --> 00:29:13.520
They used to say that
eye surgery would

00:29:13.520 --> 00:29:14.860
never really take off.

00:29:14.860 --> 00:29:16.290
Our eyes are pretty
precious to us.

00:29:16.290 --> 00:29:18.650
Not quite as much as our brain,
but we don't trivially

00:29:18.650 --> 00:29:20.050
mess with them.

00:29:20.050 --> 00:29:23.250
But the excimer laser that made
Lasik possible changed

00:29:23.250 --> 00:29:24.920
that game tremendously.

00:29:24.920 --> 00:29:28.650
Before the excemer laser, there
were less than 20,000

00:29:28.650 --> 00:29:31.090
eye surgeries done per
year in the US.

00:29:31.090 --> 00:29:33.320
Now we're over two
million per year.

00:29:33.320 --> 00:29:36.840
And the cost has gone down from
10s of thousands in the

00:29:36.840 --> 00:29:40.150
distant past to a few hundred
dollars per eye right now,

00:29:40.150 --> 00:29:41.700
depending on whether or not you
go with the very lowest

00:29:41.700 --> 00:29:44.150
bidder on this.

00:29:44.150 --> 00:29:47.860
Now is there an excimer laser
for brain surgery?

00:29:47.860 --> 00:29:50.830
I don't think there's anything
quite that dramatic, but there

00:29:50.830 --> 00:29:54.360
are technologies on the horizon
that are dramatically

00:29:54.360 --> 00:29:56.800
simplifying and speeding
up brain surgery.

00:29:56.800 --> 00:30:00.620
And the ones that I think
about are neurovascular

00:30:00.620 --> 00:30:02.010
stereotactic surgery.

00:30:02.010 --> 00:30:03.090
So what does that mean?

00:30:03.090 --> 00:30:05.630
Neurovascular means they don't
cut open your skull, and

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:07.470
instead they get to the brain
via the bloodstream.

00:30:07.470 --> 00:30:11.380
So they insert something into
normally the femoral artery,

00:30:11.380 --> 00:30:12.720
and they can work this up.

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:14.790
This is actually a diagram
for heart surgery.

00:30:14.790 --> 00:30:16.800
They could work it all the
way up into your brain.

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:19.280
And they've been doing this
for aneurysms for the last

00:30:19.280 --> 00:30:20.450
several years.

00:30:20.450 --> 00:30:23.630
It has dramatically reduced
the length of surgery, the

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:27.040
hospital stays, the cost,
and the risk.

00:30:27.040 --> 00:30:29.830
Because cutting open your skull
is serious business.

00:30:29.830 --> 00:30:32.560
The other part of this is what
we call stereotactic surgery,

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:35.920
which means that the probe is
being guided by magnets.

00:30:35.920 --> 00:30:38.030
So it happens in a fancy-looking
operating room

00:30:38.030 --> 00:30:40.950
like this, probably not quite
as clean and perfect,

00:30:40.950 --> 00:30:43.380
hopefully with some doctors
in it as well.

00:30:43.380 --> 00:30:47.020
But the doctors actually sit
at a terminal and use a

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:49.470
joystick to move the probe.

00:30:49.470 --> 00:30:52.140
The probe itself has a camera
on it so they can see.

00:30:52.140 --> 00:30:54.130
There's an imager that shows
them where it is on a

00:30:54.130 --> 00:30:55.180
cross-section of the body.

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:58.530
And then the large device around
this person is using a

00:30:58.530 --> 00:31:01.910
shifting magnetic field to pull
the probe along in the

00:31:01.910 --> 00:31:05.020
direction the doctor wants to
go with the joystick, rather

00:31:05.020 --> 00:31:10.120
than this clunky old cutting
and so on and so forth.

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:14.080
One of the real luminaries in
neuroscience, a guy by the

00:31:14.080 --> 00:31:16.790
name of Rodolfo Llinas, who's
the editor of a journal called

00:31:16.790 --> 00:31:19.990
Neuron, has proposed that we
could use this to build a very

00:31:19.990 --> 00:31:21.720
advanced brain-computer
interface.

00:31:21.720 --> 00:31:26.610
What he points out is that
nanotubes are essentially

00:31:26.610 --> 00:31:29.780
excellent wires, and are
very, very, very small.

00:31:29.780 --> 00:31:30.925
These aren't even nanotubes.

00:31:30.925 --> 00:31:33.810
These are nanowires that are
much bigger than a nanotube,

00:31:33.810 --> 00:31:36.000
but they're still very,
very, very small.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.200
In fact, each of these is
about a quarter of the

00:31:38.200 --> 00:31:41.140
diameter of the wavelength
of visible light.

00:31:41.140 --> 00:31:44.130
Visible light is about 400-ish
nanometers, and these are

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:46.280
about 50 nanometers across.

00:31:46.280 --> 00:31:48.950
These are so small that a bundle
of a million of them

00:31:48.950 --> 00:31:52.100
would take up only about 1% of
the cross sectional area of

00:31:52.100 --> 00:31:54.730
the smallest capillary
in your body.

00:31:54.730 --> 00:31:57.020
So Llinas says, hey, let's stick
in a bundle of a million

00:31:57.020 --> 00:31:59.730
of these, work it up into your
brain, and then use the

00:31:59.730 --> 00:32:02.460
magnets to make it spread out
and touch a million different

00:32:02.460 --> 00:32:04.600
neurons in your brain
all at once.

00:32:04.600 --> 00:32:07.530
And he is starting to do animal
studies investigating

00:32:07.530 --> 00:32:08.610
this technology.

00:32:08.610 --> 00:32:12.520
And we'll see if that's a viable
path to dramatically

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:14.830
increase the bandwidth in
and out of the brain.

00:32:14.830 --> 00:32:17.560
And this gets closer to the
technology of Nexis.

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:20.390
So those are the hardware
issues.

00:32:20.390 --> 00:32:21.720
But let's talk about software.

00:32:21.720 --> 00:32:24.730
Some of us work on
software, right?

00:32:24.730 --> 00:32:28.310
We all know that software is
absolutely perfect, especially

00:32:28.310 --> 00:32:29.950
Microsoft software.

00:32:29.950 --> 00:32:31.380
I'll point at myself
a little bit here.

00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:33.730
