screen myself.

00:32:33.730 --> 00:32:35.590
I don't know, it's
a myth, I think.

00:32:35.590 --> 00:32:37.880
But what does it mean if the
software running in your

00:32:37.880 --> 00:32:39.720
brain, or even just the software
your brain is talking

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:42.140
to, suddenly crashes?

00:32:42.140 --> 00:32:49.480
What does that mean if you
get malware or a virus?

00:32:49.480 --> 00:32:52.150
That could be a little bit
more serious when it's

00:32:52.150 --> 00:32:54.460
something running inside
your brain.

00:32:54.460 --> 00:32:56.330
And in fact some of this
has been shown.

00:32:56.330 --> 00:32:59.560
Anyone know who this is?

00:32:59.560 --> 00:33:02.000
This is a fellow named
Barnaby Jack.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:06.220
He's famous mostly for this hack
he did on the stage at

00:33:06.220 --> 00:33:09.880
Black Hat I think in 2010, where
from across the stage,

00:33:09.880 --> 00:33:14.430
he made this ATM just start
spewing out bills.

00:33:14.430 --> 00:33:17.870
But lately Barnaby's been
interested in medical devices

00:33:17.870 --> 00:33:19.580
and the security around them.

00:33:19.580 --> 00:33:22.360
So in 2011 he did this hack.

00:33:22.360 --> 00:33:25.750
What he's got in his hand is
a custom-built antenna,

00:33:25.750 --> 00:33:26.590
essentially.

00:33:26.590 --> 00:33:31.420
And what he's figured out that
he can do is that wirelessly,

00:33:31.420 --> 00:33:35.850
he can discover any insulin pump
by Medtronic, the number

00:33:35.850 --> 00:33:39.920
one manufacturer, within several
blocks of himself, can

00:33:39.920 --> 00:33:43.350
sniff out their IDs, get root
access, and make them do

00:33:43.350 --> 00:33:47.720
whatever he wants, including
pump out all 300 units of

00:33:47.720 --> 00:33:50.620
insulin that they have inside of
them, which for a diabetic

00:33:50.620 --> 00:33:53.570
would be lethal.

00:33:53.570 --> 00:33:54.030
That was 2011.

00:33:54.030 --> 00:33:59.430
In 2012, he did another hack
with a leading pacemaker model

00:33:59.430 --> 00:34:02.095
where he demonstrated that in a
smaller range, within about

00:34:02.095 --> 00:34:07.270
50 feet, he could cause it to
drop a 730-volt discharge into

00:34:07.270 --> 00:34:09.690
the person wearing it, which
would also be lethal.

00:34:09.690 --> 00:34:12.380
And in fact, do any of
you watch Homeland?

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:14.540
I'm going to give a spoiler, so
go la, la, la if you don't

00:34:14.540 --> 00:34:15.610
want to hear this.

00:34:15.610 --> 00:34:16.639
In a recent--

00:34:16.639 --> 00:34:18.469
I don't watch the show, but
I'm told that in a recent

00:34:18.469 --> 00:34:23.280
episode, they assassinated the
vice president by remotely

00:34:23.280 --> 00:34:24.679
turning off his pacemaker.

00:34:24.679 --> 00:34:26.560
And if you recall, Dick Cheney,
when he was vice

00:34:26.560 --> 00:34:29.070
president, for quite a
while, had no pulse.

00:34:29.070 --> 00:34:32.830
He was in continuous cardiac
failure and instead he had an

00:34:32.830 --> 00:34:35.760
implanted pump that moved
his blood around.

00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:38.250
I don't know what
APIs that had.

00:34:38.250 --> 00:34:42.800
But science fiction sounds more
and more like real life.

00:34:42.800 --> 00:34:45.170
So security is a very
big challenge.

00:34:45.170 --> 00:34:47.100
That's one of the things that
the book gets into a little

00:34:47.100 --> 00:34:49.929
bit, is what happens when people
can reroute your brain

00:34:49.929 --> 00:34:52.290
or somebody else's.

00:34:52.290 --> 00:34:54.699
But the biggest question I think
of all of the stuff, as

00:34:54.699 --> 00:34:57.500
it comes to pass, as I think it
will, is what's the impact

00:34:57.500 --> 00:34:58.980
on society?

00:34:58.980 --> 00:35:02.540
So the printing press is very
old information technology and

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:03.630
it's had marvelous effects.

00:35:03.630 --> 00:35:05.140
Let's talk about two effects.

00:35:05.140 --> 00:35:06.990
It supercharged innovation.

00:35:06.990 --> 00:35:10.200
By allowing ideas to spread from
person to person, it just

00:35:10.200 --> 00:35:12.465
accelerated the rate of
invention, the rate of

00:35:12.465 --> 00:35:13.530
knowledge dissemination.

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:15.580
And it didn't start
the Renaissance.

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:16.450
Some other things did.

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:18.580
But it really powered through,
and the scientific

00:35:18.580 --> 00:35:20.180
revolution, and so on.

00:35:20.180 --> 00:35:24.600
It also was a great tool of
anti-authoritarianism.

00:35:24.600 --> 00:35:27.320
So it's famous, the first thing
printed on the printing

00:35:27.320 --> 00:35:29.250
press was the Gutenberg Bible.

00:35:29.250 --> 00:35:32.450
Definitely a tool of authority,
if you will.

00:35:32.450 --> 00:35:37.270
One of the later things printed
on it was Martin

00:35:37.270 --> 00:35:40.780
Luther's list of complaints
about the Catholic Church, his

00:35:40.780 --> 00:35:44.060
pamphlets which he then nailed
to the doors of churches and

00:35:44.060 --> 00:35:45.890
led to the creation of the
Protestant Church and the

00:35:45.890 --> 00:35:47.910
erosion of power of the
Catholic Church.

00:35:47.910 --> 00:35:51.550
It was also used to print the
Revolutionary pamphlets in the

00:35:51.550 --> 00:35:54.740
late 1700s of the founding
fathers of this country.

00:35:54.740 --> 00:35:57.560
So overall, information
technology has been a very

00:35:57.560 --> 00:36:00.370
anti-authoritarian thing
in this context.

00:36:00.370 --> 00:36:02.150
But it wasn't always so.

00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:05.140
The very first information
technologies created by the

00:36:05.140 --> 00:36:07.280
Sumerians and Egyptians
were in the hands

00:36:07.280 --> 00:36:09.080
of a very few people.

00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:13.850
And they more allowed for the
creation of empire and the

00:36:13.850 --> 00:36:17.150
clamping down on the freedoms
of the individual than the

00:36:17.150 --> 00:36:20.430
other way around, again, because
only a small minority

00:36:20.430 --> 00:36:24.190
had access to and control over
and the ability to use this

00:36:24.190 --> 00:36:25.610
technology.

00:36:25.610 --> 00:36:27.440
So today we have that
conflict about

00:36:27.440 --> 00:36:30.650
information tech currently.

00:36:30.650 --> 00:36:34.200
During the Arab Spring, this
picture made its way around, I

00:36:34.200 --> 00:36:37.450
think taken from a
place in Egypt.

00:36:37.450 --> 00:36:39.840
Revolution tools, no longer
the AK-47, no longer the

00:36:39.840 --> 00:36:43.610
machete, now Twitter
and Facebook.

00:36:43.610 --> 00:36:45.380
And to a certain extent,
this is true.

00:36:45.380 --> 00:36:48.470
Wael Ghonim, who was one of
the people behind the Arab

00:36:48.470 --> 00:36:51.980
Spring, talks about how one of
the things that started this

00:36:51.980 --> 00:36:57.070
was a video taken of police
beating up a student in

00:36:57.070 --> 00:37:01.290
Alexandria, which was then
posted to YouTube and then

00:37:01.290 --> 00:37:03.100
made its way onto Facebook.

00:37:03.100 --> 00:37:04.880
And the first Arab
Spring protest--

00:37:04.880 --> 00:37:05.430
in Egypt, anyway.

00:37:05.430 --> 00:37:06.480
It was the second country.

00:37:06.480 --> 00:37:09.440
But the first ones there were
organized as a protest about

00:37:09.440 --> 00:37:12.920
this kid's beating, and it
was a Facebook event.

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:16.580
On the other hand, people will
tell you that in Iran, the

00:37:16.580 --> 00:37:20.030
authorities have used Twitter
and Facebook to track down

00:37:20.030 --> 00:37:23.190
people who are saying
anti-authoritarian things.

00:37:23.190 --> 00:37:26.425
So we still have this big
question of to what extent and

00:37:26.425 --> 00:37:30.020
in what situations will
information technology be used

00:37:30.020 --> 00:37:32.780
as a tool of liberation versus
a tool of building

00:37:32.780 --> 00:37:34.180
something like 1984.

00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:36.570
And that's the question I think
I try to most get that

00:37:36.570 --> 00:37:39.430
in hopefully a fun
way in the novel.

00:37:39.430 --> 00:37:40.690
And I am an optimist.

00:37:40.690 --> 00:37:44.140
I think that by and large, this
sort of technology, a

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:46.030
more intimate means of
communicating than ever

00:37:46.030 --> 00:37:49.360
before, will be a hugely
positive thing for society.

00:37:49.360 --> 00:37:52.900
But we have to be on the lookout
for and guard against

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:55.210
its possible abuses as well.

00:37:55.210 --> 00:37:56.880
So that's it.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:37:58.130
Thank you very much.

00:38:02.450 --> 00:38:04.520
