00:38:07.550 --> 00:38:09.950
AUDIENCE: I've read that one
of the problems with the

00:38:09.950 --> 00:38:12.700
electrode connections is that
they degrade over time.

00:38:12.700 --> 00:38:15.360
Has that gotten better
in recent years?

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:18.390
RAMEZ NAAM: Yeah, so it's
a very big question.

00:38:18.390 --> 00:38:19.710
In some ways, we don't know.

00:38:19.710 --> 00:38:22.600
So the brain doesn't like the
intrusion of electrodes.

00:38:22.600 --> 00:38:23.960
It treats them as a
foreign object.

00:38:23.960 --> 00:38:25.010
It tries to guard
against them.

00:38:25.010 --> 00:38:27.060
It builds scar tissue.

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:29.140
So there's two frontiers
on that.

00:38:29.140 --> 00:38:31.000
One is making electrodes
smaller

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:32.330
and smaller and smaller.

00:38:32.330 --> 00:38:37.030
So the newest technologies of
nano probes are about 100

00:38:37.030 --> 00:38:38.610
times smaller than
the current ones.

00:38:38.610 --> 00:38:41.030
The other is what they call
bio-compatible materials that

00:38:41.030 --> 00:38:42.450
won't break down.

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:45.230
And there's whole labs dedicated
to just that.

00:38:45.230 --> 00:38:48.522
We're still not there yet,
partially because no one has

00:38:48.522 --> 00:38:51.520
worn one of these things for
a very, very long time.

00:38:51.520 --> 00:38:53.840
So in some ways, we don't see
what all the effects will be

00:38:53.840 --> 00:38:56.720
after you've had one
for 20 or 30 years.

00:38:56.720 --> 00:38:59.080
AUDIENCE: Would you like to make
some predictions for us?

00:38:59.080 --> 00:39:00.500
RAMEZ NAAM: Oh my gosh,
predictions.

00:39:00.500 --> 00:39:03.470
I'll make a couple
predictions.

00:39:03.470 --> 00:39:11.410
By 10 years from now, the first
people with bionic eyes

00:39:11.410 --> 00:39:11.860
will be here.

00:39:11.860 --> 00:39:13.710
In fact, it's probably
closer than that.

00:39:13.710 --> 00:39:16.280
You're looking at about five
years for approval of the

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:17.680
retinal prosthesis.

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:19.680
And within 10 years, I'd say
there will be at least 100,000

00:39:19.680 --> 00:39:22.420
people that have them.

00:39:22.420 --> 00:39:27.380
In the next 10 years, the FDA
will start acquiring threat

00:39:27.380 --> 00:39:31.660
modeling and security validation
of the software and

00:39:31.660 --> 00:39:35.260
protocols on your devices.

00:39:35.260 --> 00:39:39.310
There will be in the next 10
years the growth of a kind of

00:39:39.310 --> 00:39:43.820
DIY hacking movement that wants
to hack their retinal

00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:48.510
prostheses and their cochlear
implants and so on.

00:39:48.510 --> 00:39:51.530
Those are a few.

00:39:51.530 --> 00:39:55.375
AUDIENCE: Have people done stuff
outside the spectrum

00:39:55.375 --> 00:39:58.350
that we normally see or hear?

00:39:58.350 --> 00:40:03.270
RAMEZ NAAM: Not exactly, but it
is possible to do sort of

00:40:03.270 --> 00:40:04.560
translation or shifting.

00:40:04.560 --> 00:40:08.090
So it's totally possible to take
one sensory domain and

00:40:08.090 --> 00:40:08.850
shift it to another.

00:40:08.850 --> 00:40:12.500
So we could take infrared with
a rental prosthesis, pick it

00:40:12.500 --> 00:40:15.990
up, and compress it into a very
bright red, for instance,

00:40:15.990 --> 00:40:16.450
on the screen.

00:40:16.450 --> 00:40:18.740
There's no obstacle to
that, really, at all.

00:40:18.740 --> 00:40:19.850
And you can see that.

00:40:19.850 --> 00:40:22.110
There's a brand new retinal
prosthesis that's being

00:40:22.110 --> 00:40:24.370
experimented with that does

00:40:24.370 --> 00:40:26.180
something very funky, actually.

00:40:26.180 --> 00:40:30.890
So normally, the connections in
the retina aren't numerous

00:40:30.890 --> 00:40:33.580
enough to give you the ability
to read, really.

00:40:33.580 --> 00:40:34.630
So this does something else.

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:35.620
It picks up sight.

00:40:35.620 --> 00:40:37.420
It spots Braille.

00:40:37.420 --> 00:40:41.580
It sees Braille, and it
massively zooms the Braille,

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:45.130
effectively, and feeds that in
so that blind people can take

00:40:45.130 --> 00:40:47.760
all of the books they already
have and actually look at them

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:49.040
and learn to read that way.

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:52.100
So there's all sorts of
domain shifting that

00:40:52.100 --> 00:40:54.180
you can imagine doing.

00:40:54.180 --> 00:40:54.520
AUDIENCE: One last question.

00:40:54.520 --> 00:40:57.320
When do you think we'll
beat the bandwidth of

00:40:57.320 --> 00:40:59.250
our eyes and ears?

00:40:59.250 --> 00:41:00.480
RAMEZ NAAM: That's a really
good question.

00:41:00.480 --> 00:41:01.576
When do we think we'll
be the bandwidth of

00:41:01.576 --> 00:41:01.970
our eyes and ears.

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:03.180
I think it'll be a while,
to be honest.

00:41:03.180 --> 00:41:06.520
As much as I write about this
and so on, progress on the

00:41:06.520 --> 00:41:09.760
electronics goes very, very
fast, but you're always more

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:11.230
conservative when you're
doing trials on

00:41:11.230 --> 00:41:12.690
humans or even on animals.

00:41:12.690 --> 00:41:16.170
So I think it'll be on the
outside of that 10-year

00:41:16.170 --> 00:41:19.110
spectrum, but probably not 20.

00:41:19.110 --> 00:41:20.610
BRAD TEMPLETON: There's a friend
