00:41:54.270 --> 00:41:58.250
But what do you think about
learning or the ability for

00:41:58.250 --> 00:42:03.070
somebody who's in their
50s to learn--

00:42:03.070 --> 00:42:04.530
just to pick these things
up quickly.

00:42:04.530 --> 00:42:05.860
Do you have to be young, old?

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:06.650
Is there any--

00:42:06.650 --> 00:42:07.740
RAMEZ NAAM: It's a
good question.

00:42:07.740 --> 00:42:09.000
It probably will be the
case that being

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:10.550
younger will be an advantage.

00:42:10.550 --> 00:42:13.930
But we're also getting better
on the algorithm side.

00:42:13.930 --> 00:42:17.470
And we're in that feedback
is vastly important.

00:42:17.470 --> 00:42:19.900
So the first monkey experiments,
the monkey

00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:22.330
couldn't actually see the
robot arm moving.

00:42:22.330 --> 00:42:24.530
And it never occurred to them
this was very important.

00:42:24.530 --> 00:42:26.850
So this was actually a very
famous monkey experiment where

00:42:26.850 --> 00:42:30.375
the monkey sends its brain
signals over the internet to

00:42:30.375 --> 00:42:33.040
robot arms 600 miles away, which
was a great gimmick, but

00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:34.740
it couldn't see the
thing moving.

00:42:34.740 --> 00:42:38.240
So it turns out that in most of
these systems, the learning

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:40.970
happens in both directions.

00:42:40.970 --> 00:42:42.740
The system has to adapt.

00:42:42.740 --> 00:42:43.890
It has to be calibrated,
usually

00:42:43.890 --> 00:42:45.430
intentionally, for the person.

00:42:45.430 --> 00:42:49.560
When they put in the brain
visual implant for Jens, they

00:42:49.560 --> 00:42:52.250
spend time calibrating, like
learning what each pixel is,

00:42:52.250 --> 00:42:53.580
effectively, on the grid.

00:42:53.580 --> 00:42:54.520
And they just--

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:55.890
it goes into the software.

00:42:55.890 --> 00:42:57.180
But it's also the case
that the brain

00:42:57.180 --> 00:42:58.140
adapts to these things.

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:00.120
And it can adapt pretty
darn quickly.

00:43:00.120 --> 00:43:03.260
And now Johnny Ray, the
paralyzed guy, it took them

00:43:03.260 --> 00:43:05.000
about six months to train
him to use his

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:06.410
one electrode system.

00:43:06.410 --> 00:43:10.140
Now they can get people working
pretty well in a

00:43:10.140 --> 00:43:11.940
matter of several minutes.

00:43:11.940 --> 00:43:15.000
It's fast enough-- they've done
some studies where they

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:17.670
have a brain implant for people
who are either testing

00:43:17.670 --> 00:43:19.840
it or people who are having
surgery for other reasons,

00:43:19.840 --> 00:43:22.500
usually epileptics having
oblation done.

00:43:22.500 --> 00:43:24.060
They ask their permission
to do this, and

00:43:24.060 --> 00:43:25.180
the people sign off.

00:43:25.180 --> 00:43:27.460
They'll put the thing on the
surface of their brain during

00:43:27.460 --> 00:43:30.820
the surgery, and they're have
them playing Pong with it now

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:33.900
within 15 minutes before taking
it off, in large part

00:43:33.900 --> 00:43:36.130
because the algorithms that
are interpreting what's

00:43:36.130 --> 00:43:37.890
happening have gotten
a lot better.

00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:40.120
Which really means we've gotten
better understanding of

00:43:40.120 --> 00:43:43.620
what the encoding is of these
data types, if you will,

00:43:43.620 --> 00:43:45.780
inside the brain.

00:43:45.780 --> 00:43:46.592
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:43:46.592 --> 00:43:47.842
RAMEZ NAAM: Yeah.

00:43:52.420 --> 00:43:54.760
AUDIENCE: --books from, I don't
