it logarithmic?

00:46:56.720 --> 00:46:58.240
Is it linear?

00:46:58.240 --> 00:46:59.250
How does that all?

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:01.380
RAMEZ NAAM: So it differs
by sense.

00:47:01.380 --> 00:47:04.340
And the senses are going to be
a lot easier than the higher

00:47:04.340 --> 00:47:05.980
functions because we can
kind of understand

00:47:05.980 --> 00:47:06.910
what the coding means.

00:47:06.910 --> 00:47:11.940
So in vision it is pretty much
spatial, in V1, the visual

00:47:11.940 --> 00:47:13.260
area in the back of your head.

00:47:13.260 --> 00:47:14.860
But it's spatial with
some caveats.

00:47:14.860 --> 00:47:16.870
Things are not entirely
spatial.

00:47:16.870 --> 00:47:18.580
It's kind of more spatial
if you took the grid and

00:47:18.580 --> 00:47:19.230
flattened it.

00:47:19.230 --> 00:47:20.440
But then your arms, of course,
are all kind of

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:21.430
squiggly and so on.

00:47:21.430 --> 00:47:24.160
And then some neurons, they
are more including certain

00:47:24.160 --> 00:47:26.910
colors, and more encoding
motion, so with those caveats.

00:47:26.910 --> 00:47:27.845
And we kind of--

00:47:27.845 --> 00:47:30.910
I wouldn't say there's a
formalism of that encoding.

00:47:30.910 --> 00:47:32.540
It's just that we've gotten
better and better at having

00:47:32.540 --> 00:47:35.520
code that can actually
translate that.

00:47:35.520 --> 00:47:38.990
In audio, we think that
the encoding is

00:47:38.990 --> 00:47:40.090
the frequency domain.

00:47:40.090 --> 00:47:42.700
So as you shift from one region
to another, it gets

00:47:42.700 --> 00:47:44.470
more and more towards
representation of higher and

00:47:44.470 --> 00:47:46.290
higher frequencies.

00:47:46.290 --> 00:47:48.940
In motion, it's more
complex than that.

00:47:48.940 --> 00:47:51.560
But one thing that's nice in all
of these, like a general

00:47:51.560 --> 00:47:54.510
characteristic we're finding
is that we can get good

00:47:54.510 --> 00:47:56.520
results with very sparse
connections.

00:47:56.520 --> 00:47:57.820
In any given region,
we're sampling a

00:47:57.820 --> 00:47:59.790
very, very tiny bit.

00:47:59.790 --> 00:48:02.960
So it's not a very
fragile protocol.

00:48:02.960 --> 00:48:06.290
It's a very robust protocol
that just gets higher and

00:48:06.290 --> 00:48:08.760
higher resolution as you
have access to more of

00:48:08.760 --> 00:48:10.260
what's going on.

00:48:10.260 --> 00:48:13.490
And there's other stuff we know
in the higher domains

00:48:13.490 --> 00:48:15.500
even, we know some various
different things.

00:48:15.500 --> 00:48:19.870
Like in parts of your brain, you
can trace the recognition

00:48:19.870 --> 00:48:22.240
of different animals
through one

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:23.310
particular area of the brain.

00:48:23.310 --> 00:48:27.460
And you can find very reliably
that the cat versus dog areas

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:30.620
are kind of separate and in
the same relationship

00:48:30.620 --> 00:48:33.040
physically in different
people's brains.

00:48:33.040 --> 00:48:36.760
And there's even weird studies
with taking monkeys, having

00:48:36.760 --> 00:48:38.960
them look at pictures of a
cat, stimulating the dog

00:48:38.960 --> 00:48:42.360
center, and getting them to
recognize it as a dog instead.

00:48:42.360 --> 00:48:46.060
So there is very, very, very
funky stuff out there.

00:48:46.060 --> 00:48:47.450
BRAD TEMPLETON: So there's a
physical difference between

00:48:47.450 --> 00:48:49.690
cat people and dog
people then.

00:48:49.690 --> 00:48:51.750
RAMEZ NAAM: I've never seen a
correlation of is that area

00:48:51.750 --> 00:48:53.420
enlarged in one or the other,
but that would be a great

00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:53.560
study, Brad.

00:48:53.560 --> 00:48:54.660
Let's put in a grant.

00:48:54.660 --> 00:48:55.470
BRAD TEMPLETON: That's right.

00:48:55.470 --> 00:48:58.500
I want to ask about mind
control, because you love mind

00:48:58.500 --> 00:49:02.020
control and it plays
a role in the book.

00:49:02.020 --> 00:49:05.190
And not just, though, in forced
mind control, but the

00:49:05.190 --> 00:49:08.640
concept of voluntary mind
control, people wanting to

00:49:08.640 --> 00:49:11.260
change their attitudes,
people wanting to--

00:49:11.260 --> 00:49:13.200
or socially pressured
to do so.

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:16.160
For example, there's a hormone
that makes some animals more

00:49:16.160 --> 00:49:17.330
monogamous.

00:49:17.330 --> 00:49:19.330
If that applied-- or a gene
therapy like that applied in

00:49:19.330 --> 00:49:21.900
humans, you could see it being
part of the wedding vows.

00:49:21.900 --> 00:49:25.150
Why won't you take this
treatment that makes you love

00:49:25.150 --> 00:49:26.460
me forever, darling?

00:49:26.460 --> 00:49:29.180
You love me, right?

00:49:29.180 --> 00:49:31.710
What do you think about the
potential for mind control

00:49:31.710 --> 00:49:32.910
from these?

00:49:32.910 --> 00:49:33.930
RAMEZ NAAM: That's
the vasopressin

00:49:33.930 --> 00:49:35.550
receptor gene, right?

00:49:35.550 --> 00:49:38.870
Naked voles are one of the only
annals we found that's

00:49:38.870 --> 00:49:40.810
really monogamous.

00:49:40.810 --> 00:49:43.250
Yeah, I think people
will do it.

00:49:43.250 --> 00:49:45.200
There was a time in my life
that I would have-- that I

00:49:45.200 --> 00:49:47.400
felt like I was not very
outgoing or not very

00:49:47.400 --> 00:49:48.170
adventurous.

00:49:48.170 --> 00:49:50.860
And if I had an option to
change my dopamine DDR2

00:49:50.860 --> 00:49:54.580
receptor and suddenly want to
go skydiving all the time, I

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:55.830
probably would have done it.

00:49:55.830 --> 00:49:57.400
I might now.

00:49:57.400 --> 00:50:01.380
So I think people will
voluntarily engage in

00:50:01.380 --> 00:50:03.000
technologies that will allow
them to change their own

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:04.690
personalities all the time.

00:50:04.690 --> 00:50:07.510
Or for that matter, I want
something that's going to get

00:50:07.510 --> 00:50:11.460
me out of bed and to the
gym reliably every day.

00:50:11.460 --> 00:50:12.360
It's better than a
workout buddy.

00:50:12.360 --> 00:50:14.550
You've got a little app on your
brain that's like, up,

00:50:14.550 --> 00:50:15.800
here we go.

00:50:18.820 --> 00:50:20.970
AUDIENCE: So question
on that vein.

00:50:20.970 --> 00:50:23.240
It's already bewildering
difficult to keep track of the

00:50:23.240 --> 00:50:26.130
options we have in life, with
the internet and so forth.

00:50:26.130 --> 00:50:29.480
So this is a future where
everybody has to understand

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:31.130
how the brain works and
what their options are

00:50:31.130 --> 00:50:32.710
for changing it.

00:50:32.710 --> 00:50:34.970
RAMEZ NAAM: Not necessarily.

00:50:34.970 --> 00:50:37.540
I would say most people who use
apps and their phone don't

00:50:37.540 --> 00:50:38.750
understand how their
phone works.

00:50:38.750 --> 00:50:40.690
They have to have some
understanding of some

00:50:40.690 --> 00:50:42.460
abstractions about the phone.

00:50:42.460 --> 00:50:44.680
But they don't have to be
neuroscientists of the phone.

00:50:44.680 --> 00:50:47.340
They don't have to be EEs
to know, like, oh, I

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:48.520
really like this app.

00:50:48.520 --> 00:50:50.830
Or no, this kind of thing is
possible, they have to figure

00:50:50.830 --> 00:50:51.400
out some things.

00:50:51.400 --> 00:50:54.110
Like, eventually people really
need to understand, is the

00:50:54.110 --> 00:50:55.610
data in the cloud or
on their machine?

00:50:55.610 --> 00:50:58.150
Because someday they might
not have signal.

00:50:58.150 --> 00:51:01.510
So they have to learn some
things about what's going on.

00:51:01.510 --> 00:51:03.590
But they don't have to learn
all the deep details.

00:51:03.590 --> 00:51:07.410
But I agree that the future gets
more and more bewildering

00:51:07.410 --> 00:51:09.360
and that's a challenge.

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:13.930
AUDIENCE: I wonder if we know
anything about memory.

00:51:13.930 --> 00:51:15.290
Like is there some way--

00:51:15.290 --> 00:51:18.640
is any research into, like,
adding a hard drive to your

00:51:18.640 --> 00:51:19.230
brain, basically?

00:51:19.230 --> 00:51:21.130
Because you've talked a
lot about processors.

00:51:21.130 --> 00:51:22.400
RAMEZ NAAM: That's what
people want to do.

00:51:22.400 --> 00:51:24.300
I think it's going
to be tough.

00:51:24.300 --> 00:51:26.100
We don't understand
a whole lot.

00:51:26.100 --> 00:51:30.040
But just like with vision and
sound and motion, the way that

00:51:30.040 --> 00:51:34.100
we've actually made progress on
the encoding is trying to

00:51:34.100 --> 00:51:37.020
repair these things in people
that have some sort of damage.

00:51:37.020 --> 00:51:39.520
So that's the most encouraging
thing about the rat study and

00:51:39.520 --> 00:51:43.450
so on, is that doing the work to
try to fix the damage will

00:51:43.450 --> 00:51:47.220
functionally teach us more and
more about the encoding.

00:51:47.220 --> 00:51:49.070
But today I'd say we
know relatively

00:51:49.070 --> 00:51:50.566
little, to be honest.

00:51:50.566 --> 00:51:52.350
BRAD TEMPLETON: We used to
know more yesterday.

00:51:52.350 --> 00:51:53.670
RAMEZ NAAM: It's possible,
some of us.

00:51:57.090 --> 00:51:59.030
AUDIENCE: How does this change
your ideas about death?

00:51:59.030 --> 00:52:01.720
And what do you--

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:04.870
let's say we build AI machines
in the future.

00:52:04.870 --> 00:52:07.380
How do we deal with the problem
that our biological

00:52:07.380 --> 00:52:09.360
bodies are going to die?

00:52:09.360 --> 00:52:12.060
RAMEZ NAAM: Well it's not really
exactly in this domain.

00:52:12.060 --> 00:52:14.280
But I guess it's a large
extension of it, is I believe

00:52:14.280 --> 00:52:15.890
uploading is possible.

00:52:15.890 --> 00:52:18.690
Everything we know says that if
you had a complete map of

00:52:18.690 --> 00:52:21.040
your brain down to the molecular
level, at least, and

00:52:21.040 --> 00:52:23.420
we could simulate it,
we'd have a copy of

00:52:23.420 --> 00:52:24.610
your thoughts running.

00:52:24.610 --> 00:52:26.580
We don't know how technically
difficult it is.

00:52:26.580 --> 00:52:27.580
You can make a guess.

00:52:27.580 --> 00:52:30.800
You can say, oh, if we get it
at the level of neurons and

00:52:30.800 --> 00:52:32.340
synapses, that's probably
good enough.

00:52:32.340 --> 00:52:32.960
We don't know.

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:34.440
We won't know until we get
there and try it, to be

00:52:34.440 --> 00:52:35.700
totally honest.

00:52:35.700 --> 00:52:37.130
So I think eventually
technology

00:52:37.130 --> 00:52:38.320
will make that possible.

00:52:38.320 --> 00:52:41.420
Ray Kurzweil thinks it's going
to be 30 years from now.

00:52:41.420 --> 00:52:42.560
It might be 100 years
from now.

00:52:42.560 --> 00:52:44.260
It might be 1,000 years now.

00:52:44.260 --> 00:52:48.730
But the brain is just another
information processor, a very

00:52:48.730 --> 00:52:50.330
messy one, a very
interesting one.

00:52:50.330 --> 00:52:52.920
And it's really, the pattern
of information is you, to a

00:52:52.920 --> 00:52:53.510
certain extent.

00:52:53.510 --> 00:52:56.250
So we can eventually
decouple those.

00:52:56.250 --> 00:53:01.406
Just exactly when is still
a very open questions.

00:53:01.406 --> 00:53:03.900
AUDIENCE: Would you feel
like that was you?

00:53:03.900 --> 00:53:07.170
RAMEZ NAAM: That copy of me
would feel that it was me.

00:53:07.170 --> 00:53:10.080
That copy of me would remember
it being me right here

00:53:10.080 --> 00:53:13.780
answering this question, and be
like, oh, I feel like me.

00:53:13.780 --> 00:53:15.620
And the other copy of me would
eventually be dead.

00:53:15.620 --> 00:53:18.950
So now, what if that copy
made 1,000 more copies?

00:53:18.950 --> 00:53:19.700
Would they all feel like me?

00:53:19.700 --> 00:53:20.430
Yes.

00:53:20.430 --> 00:53:23.320
We will have to-- here's the
philosophical thing I'll say.

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:28.350
Right now, if I'll use computer
lingo a little bit,

00:53:28.350 --> 00:53:30.610
we don't differentiate, when we
talk about me, between the

00:53:30.610 --> 00:53:33.180
class and the instance
of the class.

00:53:33.180 --> 00:53:37.500
So eventually our conception
of personhood will change.

00:53:37.500 --> 00:53:40.330
And we'll see, like, do you
believe that all other objects

00:53:40.330 --> 00:53:42.390
that are of your class
are the same as you?

00:53:42.390 --> 00:53:44.012
In some ways, yes.

00:53:44.012 --> 00:53:46.820
And we'll start to make
that differentiation.

00:53:46.820 --> 00:53:48.340
But we're not ready
for that yet.

00:53:48.340 --> 00:53:51.250
Most philosophers don't have an
object-oriented programming

00:53:51.250 --> 00:53:55.270
background, so we're not
quite ready for that.

00:53:55.270 --> 00:53:56.510
BRAD TEMPLETON: Well thanks
a lot, Mez, for coming in.

00:53:56.510 --> 00:53:56.825
RAMEZ NAAM: Awesome.

00:53:56.825 --> 00:53:58.075
Thank you all.

